<LP>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission charged a partner
in a New York law firm with trading on inside information
obtained from a client.
   In a civil complaint in federal court in Manhattan, the
SEC charged Henry A. Singer with buying 6,600 shares of
WearEver-Proctor-Silex Inc. stock at a time when the company
was discussing a management leveraged buy-out. Mr. Singer, 52
years old, is a partner in Morrison Cohen Singer &amp; Weinstein.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Singer, through his attorney, Robert G. Morvillo,
called the SEC charges "factually inaccurate and legally
deficient" and said he intends to fight them. Mr. Morvillo
said that there is "substantial documentary evidence and
corroborative testimony of several other witnesses which
confirm that Mr. Singer did not purchase WearEver stock based
on inside information."
   According to the SEC complaint, Mr. Singer bought 5,000
shares of WearEver's stock Aug. 19, 1987, at $13.25 a share,
based on information he allegedly obtained from Lawrence A.
McLernon, a member of the company's board, concerning the
proposed leveraged buy-out. The SEC said that Mr. Singer, a
corporate lawyer specializing in mergers and acquisitions,
represented Mr. McLernon and that the two were friends.
   The SEC alleged that Mr. Singer bought another 1,600
shares Nov. 2, 1987 at $9.50 each, two months after he was
retained by a special committee of WearEver's board that
included Mr. McLernon. The complaint alleges that at the time
of Mr. Singer's second purchase, he possessed nonpublic
information that indicated that there were potential
third-party bidders for WearEver that were likely to bid more
than the $18 a share that WearEver's management had offered.
   Nacco Industries Inc. acquired WearEver for $17.50 a share
in April 1988. The SEC said that after learning of the
purchase, Mr. Singer sold his stock, earning $34,050 on the
sale.
   In his statement, Mr. Singer said that he had cooperated
with the SEC's inquiry and that the SEC had chosen "either to
ignore or misconstrue all of the evidence presented to it."
Mr. Singer's law firm issued a statement saying it "stands
behind Mr. Singer."
