   AN ILLINOIS CONTRACTOR is indicted on unusual charges.
   A federal grand jury in Milwaukee indicted contractor S.A.
Healy Co. for allegedly violating federal workplace-safety
laws in connection with a 1988 explosion that killed three
Healy workers at an underground work-site.
   It is unusual for federal prosecutors to bring criminal
charges for breach of the occupational safety and health
statutes, although the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration often imposes civil penalties.
   The 12-count indictment alleges that Healy willfully
failed to properly vent a tunnel or properly instruct workers
in underground safety precautions, and failed to cut the
electricity in the tunnel after dangerous levels of methane
gas had been detected. All the counts are misdemeanors
because federal law doesn't permit prosecution of OSHA law
violations as felonies.
   "The feds are bringing the biggest guns they have against
Healy, and we appreciate and applaud" the move, says Joseph
Kinney, executive director of the Chicago-based National Safe
Workplace Institute. But, he adds, "it's ridiculous {they}
can't do more."
   Each of the 12 misdemeanor counts in the indictment
brought against Healy, based in McCook, Ill., carries a
maximum fine of $500,000.
   An attorney for Healy said the company "regrets the tragic
accident, but doesn't believe that any of its management
employees committed reckless acts." The company believes
management "will be vindicated," he says.
   Milwaukee County District Attorney E. Michael McCann,
using state law, also this week filed two charges of reckless
homicide against Healy. But he says the state's
$10,000-a-count maximum fine on such charges "is not enough."
