   MANDATORY RETIREMENT AGE upheld for New York Supreme Court
justices.
   A federal appeals court in New York reversed a lower-court
decision that had prohibited the state of New York from
forcing a state judge to retire at age 76. The federal Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission had filed the suit on
behalf of Justice Isaac Rubin, who is 77.
   The appeals court ruled that the federal age
discrimination law, under which the suit was brought, does
not apply to New York Supreme Court justices because they are
elected. The law states that it does not apply to "any person
elected to public office."
   Justice Rubin and the attorneys for the state of New York
and the EEOC declined to comment.
