   THE JUSTICE DEPARTMENT'S criminal division may get a new
chief.
   President Bush nominated Robert Mueller, a personal aide
to Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, assistant attorney
general in charge of criminal matters.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Mr. Mueller would succeed
Edward Dennis, who said he will resign Aug. 31. The change
comes shortly after a shake-up of the department's senior
staff. But Justice Department officials, including Mr.
Dennis, stressed that his departure is voluntary and
amicable.
   Mr. Mueller, a special assistant to Mr. Thornburgh on
criminal issues, previously served as a federal prosecutor in
Massachusetts and California.
   A career prosecutor, Mr. Dennis said he would return to
his hometown of Philadelphia to join the law firm of Morgan,
Lewis &amp; Bockius as a partner.
